The paper presents a deep learning framework for contextual multi-armed bandits, which involves modeling the context non-linearly and enabling principled exploration at the same time. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) and Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of Bayesian neural networks and dropout rates, which are relevant to the Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science (cs.CE) and Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-categories. Finally, the paper presents experimental results on two tasks, which suggests that it may also be relevant to the Data Structures (cs.DS) sub-category.
